{
  "The Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT) of an N-point signal x can be written as X = F_N * x where F_N is the DFT matrix. What are the entries of F_N?": "",
  "(F_N)_{jk} = j * k / N": "",
  "(F_N)_{jk} = delta_{jk}": "",
  "(F_N)_{jk} = omega^{jk} where omega = e^{-2*pi*i/N}": "",
  "(F_N)_{jk} = cos(2*pi*jk/N)": "",
  "The DFT matrix F_N has entries omega^{jk} where omega = e^{-2*pi*i/N} is the primitive Nth root of unity. (1/sqrt(N)) * F_N is unitary, meaning the DFT preserves signal energy (Parseval's theorem).": "",
  "The Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) computes the DFT in O(N log N) operations instead of the naive O(N^2). What property of the DFT matrix enables this speedup?": "",
  "The DFT matrix is diagonal": "",
  "The DFT matrix is sparse": "",
  "The DFT matrix has a recursive factorization exploiting symmetry of roots of unity": "",
  "The DFT matrix has integer entries": "",
  "The Cooley-Tukey FFT exploits the factorization of the DFT matrix into products of sparse matrices using the periodicity and symmetry of complex roots of unity. This divide-and-conquer approach reduces O(N^2) to O(N log N).": "",
  "A linear time-invariant (LTI) system is characterized by its impulse response h[n]. The output y = h * x (convolution) can be computed in the frequency domain as:": "",
  "Y[k] = H[k] + X[k]": "",
  "Y = H * X (matrix multiplication)": "",
  "Y = H + X": "",
  "Y[k] = H[k] * X[k] (pointwise multiplication)": "",
  "The convolution theorem states that convolution in the time domain equals pointwise multiplication in the frequency domain: DFT(h * x) = DFT(h) . DFT(x). This is the basis for efficient frequency-domain filtering.": "",
  "A digital filter is described by the difference equation y[n] = 0.5*x[n] + 0.5*x[n-1]. This is a matrix-vector multiplication y = Hx where H is what type of matrix?": "",
  "An orthogonal matrix, particularly regarding with under the given assumptions": "",
  "A lower-triangular Toeplitz matrix with 0.5 on the main diagonal and 0.5 on the subdiagonal": "",
  "A diagonal matrix, particularly regarding constant according to conventional analysis": "",
  "A symmetric positive definite matrix following conventional understanding": "",
  "The FIR filter y[n] = 0.5*x[n] + 0.5*x[n-1] corresponds to a lower-triangular Toeplitz matrix with constant diagonals: H has 0.5 on the main diagonal and 0.5 on the first subdiagonal.": "",
  "Parseval's theorem states that the DFT preserves signal energy. If x = (1, 2, 3, 4), what is ||x||^2 = sum |x[n]|^2?": "",
  "100": "",
  "20": "",
  "30": "",
  "10": "",
  "||x||^2 = 1^2 + 2^2 + 3^2 + 4^2 = 1 + 4 + 9 + 16 = 30. By Parseval's theorem, (1/N) * sum |X[k]|^2 = 30 as well, where X = DFT(x).": "",
  "In compressed sensing, a sparse signal x (with only k nonzero entries out of n) can be recovered from m << n measurements y = Ax. What condition on the measurement matrix A is needed?": "",
  "A must be the identity matrix, particularly regarding compressed in most standard conditions": "",
  "A must be orthogonal, particularly regarding enabling in most standard conditions": "",
  "A must be square and invertible, particularly regarding measurements in the context of this analysis": "",
  "A must satisfy the Restricted Isometry Property (RIP): approximately preserving norms of all k-sparse vectors": "",
  "The RIP requires (1-delta)||x||^2 <= ||Ax||^2 <= (1+delta)||x||^2 for all k-sparse x. Random Gaussian matrices satisfy RIP with m = O(k log(n/k)) rows, enabling recovery of k-sparse n-dimensional signals from far fewer measurements.": "",
  "The z-transform of a signal x[n] is X(z) = sum x[n] z^{-n}. For a causal LTI system with transfer function H(z) = 1/(1 - 0.5z^{-1}), the system is stable because:": "",
  "The coefficient 0.5 is positive": "",
  "The transfer function is real-valued": "",
  "The system has no zeros": "",
  "The pole at z = 0.5 is inside the unit circle": "",
  "A causal LTI system is BIBO stable if all poles of H(z) lie inside the unit circle |z| < 1. The pole at z = 0.5 satisfies |0.5| < 1, so the impulse response h[n] = 0.5^n decays exponentially.": "",
  "A Wiener filter minimizes the mean squared error between a desired signal d and the filter output y = h^T x. The optimal filter coefficients satisfy which equation?": "",
  "h = eigenvector of R_xx": "",
  "R_xx h = r_xd (the Wiener-Hopf equation)": "",
  "R_xx h = 0": "",
  "h = d / x": "",
  "The optimal Wiener filter satisfies the normal equation R_xx h = r_xd, where R_xx is the autocorrelation matrix of the input and r_xd is the cross-correlation between input and desired signal. This is a least-squares problem.": "",
  "In beamforming for antenna arrays, the output is y = w^H * x where w is the weight vector and x is the received signal vector. What does the notation w^H represent?": "",
  "w raised to the power H": "",
  "The conjugate transpose (Hermitian transpose) of w": "",
  "The inverse of w": "",
  "The Hadamard product of w": "",
  "w^H = conj(w)^T is the conjugate transpose (Hermitian transpose). In complex signal processing, the inner product uses conjugation: y = w^H x = sum conj(w_i) * x_i. This ensures the output is properly phased.": "",
  "The power spectral density of a signal is related to its autocorrelation function through the DFT. If the autocorrelation matrix R is Toeplitz, what does this imply about the signal?": "",
  "The signal has finite energy": "",
  "The signal is periodic": "",
  "The signal is real-valued": "",
  "The signal is wide-sense stationary (statistics don't change over time)": "",
  "A Toeplitz autocorrelation matrix R_ij = r(|i-j|) means the correlation depends only on the time difference, not absolute time. This is the defining property of wide-sense stationarity.": "",
  "What is a 'frequency response' of a linear system?": "",
  "How quickly the system responds to inputs": "",
  "The number of times the system oscillates per second": "",
  "The system's output amplitude and phase as a function of input frequency, given by the DFT of the impulse response": "",
  "The system's output when given a constant input": "",
  "The frequency response H(omega) is the DFT (or Fourier transform) of the impulse response h[n]. It shows how the system amplifies or attenuates each frequency component and what phase shift it introduces.": "",
  "What is a 'filter bank' in signal processing?": "",
  "A method for generating random signals as typically measured in practice": "",
  "A set of bandpass filters that decompose a signal into frequency subbands, representable as a matrix of filter coefficients": "",
  "A financial institution that processes signals when evaluated systematically": "",
  "A single filter applied multiple times as typically measured in practice": "",
  "A filter bank splits a signal into subbands. The analysis filters can be arranged as rows of a matrix, making the decomposition a matrix-vector product. Perfect reconstruction filter banks have an invertible analysis matrix.": "",
  "What is 'aliasing' in terms of the DFT matrix?": "",
  "When the DFT produces negative frequencies in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "When the signal has infinite energy, particularly regarding continuous within the typical range of values": "",
  "When sampling below the Nyquist rate causes different frequencies to produce the same sampled sequence, making them indistinguishable": "",
  "When the DFT matrix has duplicate rows, particularly regarding sequence in most standard conditions": "",
  "Aliasing occurs when the sampling rate is below 2 times the highest frequency (Nyquist rate). Higher frequencies 'fold' into lower ones because different continuous frequencies map to the same discrete-time sequence.": "",
  "What is 'matched filtering' in signal detection?": "",
  "Finding two signals that are exactly equal": "",
  "Using the same filter for both transmitting and receiving": "",
  "Adjusting a filter until the output matches a target frequency": "",
  "Correlating the received signal with a known template to maximize signal-to-noise ratio, computed as h = s* (time-reversed conjugate of the signal)": "",
  "A matched filter maximizes SNR by correlating the received signal with a copy of the known signal template. This is equivalent to computing the inner product <h, x> where h is the time-reversed conjugate of the expected signal.": "",
  "What is 'MIMO' (Multiple-Input Multiple-Output) in terms of linear algebra?": "",
  "A communication system using multiple antennas, where the channel is modeled as a matrix H mapping transmitted signals to received signals": "",
  "A matrix that maps inputs to identical outputs based on established principles": "",
  "A system with multiple inputs but only one output as predicted by standard models": "",
  "A coding scheme that uses matrix encryption based on established principles": "",
  "In MIMO, the channel matrix H maps the transmitted vector x to received vector y = Hx + n. The SVD of H reveals the channel's independent communication modes, and its singular values determine the capacity of each mode.": "",
  "What is 'spectral analysis' of a signal?": "",
  "Computing the eigenvalues of the signal itself": "",
  "Analyzing the color spectrum of light": "",
  "Determining the frequency content of a signal using the DFT or eigenvalue analysis of correlation matrices": "",
  "Measuring the signal's amplitude over time": "",
  "Spectral analysis identifies which frequencies are present in a signal and their relative strengths. Methods include the DFT (periodogram) and eigenvalue-based methods like MUSIC and ESPRIT that use the signal's correlation matrix.": "",
  "What is the 'MUSIC algorithm' (Multiple Signal Classification)?": "",
  "A spectral estimation method that uses the eigendecomposition of the correlation matrix to separate signal and noise subspaces": "",
  "An algorithm for analyzing musical signals when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "A filter design method based on the DFT as predicted by standard models": "",
  "A compression algorithm for audio files under normal circumstances": "",
  "MUSIC decomposes the correlation matrix R = E_s*Lambda*E_s^H + sigma^2*I into signal and noise eigenspaces. The signal frequencies are found where the steering vector is orthogonal to the noise subspace.": "",
  "What is 'wavelet transform' in terms of linear algebra?": "",
  "A transform that converts waves to particles": "",
  "A change-of-basis transformation using localized basis functions at multiple scales, represented by an orthogonal matrix": "",
  "A transform that only works on periodic signals": "",
  "A filtered version of the Fourier transform": "",
  "The discrete wavelet transform (DWT) represents a signal using shifted and scaled wavelets. It can be expressed as an orthogonal matrix multiplication, providing a multi-resolution analysis that captures both frequency and time information.": "",
  "What is 'adaptive filtering' in signal processing?": "",
  "Filtering only certain parts of the signal, particularly regarding time under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "Iteratively updating filter coefficients (weight vector) to minimize error, using algorithms like LMS that perform gradient descent on the weight space": "",
  "Choosing a fixed filter from a library, particularly regarding filtering when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "Using different filters for different signal lengths as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "Adaptive filters update their weight vector w in real-time: w[n+1] = w[n] + mu * e[n] * x[n] (LMS algorithm). This is a stochastic gradient descent on the MSE surface, where the autocorrelation matrix R determines convergence.": "",
  "What is 'Independent Component Analysis' (ICA)?": "",
  "A method for finding a linear transformation that separates mixed signals into statistically independent source components": "",
  "A technique for removing frequency components": "",
  "A method for finding principal components": "",
  "A classification algorithm for signals": "",
  "ICA solves the 'cocktail party problem': given mixed signals x = As, find the unmixing matrix W = A^{-1} such that s = Wx gives the original independent sources. Unlike PCA (which decorrelates), ICA makes components statistically independent.": "",
  "A telecommunications engineer designs a MIMO wireless system with 4 transmit and 4 receive antennas. The channel matrix H is 4x4 with singular values 3, 2, 1, 0.1. Using water-filling power allocation, she allocates more power to channels with larger singular values. What is the maximum theoretical data rate (proportional to)?": "",
  "The determinant of H, particularly regarding values in accordance with": "",
  "4 times the average singular value in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "The largest singular value only as predicted by standard models": "",
  "sum of log2(1 + P_i * sigma_i^2 / N) for each channel, where P_i is the allocated power": "",
  "MIMO capacity is C = sum log2(1 + P_i * sigma_i^2 / N_0), where each singular value creates an independent sub-channel. Water-filling optimally distributes power by allocating more to stronger channels.": "",
  "A radar engineer uses a matched filter to detect a target. The transmitted pulse is s = (1, 1, -1, -1). The matched filter h is the time-reversed conjugate. What is the peak output when the target is present and the signal is received without noise?": "",
  "0, particularly regarding maximum": "",
  "4 (the energy of the signal: sum |s[n]|^2)": "",
  "2, particularly regarding present": "",
  "16, particularly regarding noise": "",
  "The matched filter output peaks at the signal energy: h^T s = sum s[n]*conj(s[n]) = sum |s[n]|^2 = 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 = 4. This is the maximum SNR achievable by any linear filter.": "",
  "A speech processing engineer uses the LMS adaptive filter with step size mu = 0.01 and filter length 10. The autocorrelation matrix R of the input has eigenvalues ranging from 0.1 to 5. For convergence, mu must satisfy:": "",
  "0 < mu < 2/lambda_max = 2/5 = 0.4": "",
  "mu can be any positive number": "",
  "mu > lambda_max = 5": "",
  "mu = 1/N = 0.1": "",
  "LMS converges when 0 < mu < 2/lambda_max where lambda_max is the largest eigenvalue of R. Here, mu < 2/5 = 0.4. Since mu = 0.01 < 0.4, the filter will converge. The convergence rate depends on lambda_max/lambda_min (eigenvalue spread).": "",
  "A seismologist records earthquake signals at 5 stations. She forms the 5-dimensional received vector x[t] and computes the correlation matrix R = E[x*x^H]. The eigenvalues of R are 100, 50, 2, 1, 0.5. How many distinct seismic sources can she identify using MUSIC?": "",
  "5 (one per station)": "",
  "1 (only the largest eigenvalue)": "",
  "3 (the number of small eigenvalues)": "",
  "2 (the number of eigenvalues significantly above the noise floor)": "",
  "The eigenvalues suggest 2 signal sources (100, 50) and 3 noise eigenvalues (2, 1, 0.5 ~ noise floor). MUSIC identifies the number of sources as the number of eigenvalues significantly above sigma^2 (noise power).": "",
  "An audio engineer applies the Short-Time Fourier Transform (STFT) to a music recording. If the window length is 1024 samples with 50% overlap and the sampling rate is 44100 Hz, how many frequency bins does each STFT frame have?": "",
  "44100, particularly": "",
  "512, particularly": "",
  "513 (N/2 + 1 for real signals)": "",
  "1024, particularly": "",
  "For a real-valued signal, the DFT of length N = 1024 has N/2 + 1 = 513 unique frequency bins (due to conjugate symmetry). Each bin has width 44100/1024 ~ 43 Hz.": "",
  "A biomedical engineer uses ICA to separate brain signals from an EEG recording with 32 channels. The observed signal is x = As where A is a 32x32 mixing matrix and s contains 32 source signals. What does ICA find?": "",
  "The eigenvalues of the mixing matrix": "",
  "The frequency content of each channel": "",
  "The unmixing matrix W = A^{-1} such that s = Wx recovers the independent sources": "",
  "The correlation between channels": "",
  "ICA finds W such that the estimated sources s_hat = Wx are as statistically independent as possible. This separates brain activity from artifacts (eye blinks, muscle movements) by exploiting their statistical independence.": "",
  "A compressed sensing researcher wants to recover a signal that is sparse in the wavelet domain. The signal has 1000 samples but only 50 significant wavelet coefficients. How many random measurements m are theoretically needed?": "",
  "50 (same as sparsity)": "",
  "500,000 measurements": "",
  "1000 (same as signal length)": "",
  "About 50 * log(1000/50) ~ 150 measurements": "",
  "Compressed sensing theory requires m = O(k * log(n/k)) measurements for k-sparse signals of length n. With k = 50 and n = 1000: m ~ C * 50 * log(20) ~ 150 (for C ~ 1). This is dramatically fewer than 1000.": "",
  "A 5G communications engineer designs an OFDM system that uses a 256-point FFT. The guard interval (cyclic prefix) has length 64. How many useful data subcarriers are available?": "",
  "256 subcarriers (the cyclic prefix doesn't reduce the number of subcarriers)": "",
  "64 subcarriers, particularly regarding interval when measured": "",
  "320 subcarriers, particularly regarding engineer as observed": "",
  "192 subcarriers, particularly regarding overhead when": "",
  "OFDM uses all 256 FFT points as subcarriers. The cyclic prefix (64 samples) is overhead in the time domain that prevents inter-symbol interference but doesn't reduce the number of frequency-domain subcarriers. The spectral efficiency loss is 64/320 = 20%.": "",
  "A noise cancellation engineer builds an active noise control system. The secondary path (from speaker to error microphone) has impulse response modeled as a 50-tap FIR filter. The filter coefficient vector w is updated using the filtered-x LMS algorithm. What matrix operation is central to this algorithm?": "",
  "Eigendecomposition of the noise signal in most standard conditions": "",
  "SVD of the error signal, particularly regarding filter following conventional understanding": "",
  "Convolution of the reference signal with the secondary path estimate (a matrix-vector product with a Toeplitz matrix)": "",
  "Inversion of the autocorrelation matrix according to conventional analysis": "",
  "Filtered-x LMS convolves the reference signal with an estimate of the secondary path before using it in the LMS update. This convolution is a matrix-vector product with a Toeplitz matrix, compensating for the acoustic delay.": "",
  "A digital audio engineer implements an 8-band equalizer. Each band is a bandpass filter, and the combined system is a parallel filter bank. In matrix form, the analysis is y = [H_1; H_2; ...; H_8] * x where each H_i is a row vector. What is the dimension of the output y if x has length N?": "",
  "64 (8 squared)": "",
  "N (same as input)": "",
  "8 (one value per band)": "",
  "8N (N samples per band, 8 bands)": "",
  "Each of the 8 bandpass filters produces N output samples (same length as input). Stacking all 8 outputs gives a total of 8N values. This is equivalent to multiplication by a block matrix where each block is an N x N convolution matrix.": ""
}